# Deep fascia

Deep fascia (or investing fascia ) is a [fascia](/Fascia), a layer of [dense connective tissue](/Dense_connective_tissue) that can surround individual [muscles](/Muscle) and groups of muscles to separate into [fascial compartments](/Fascial_compartment). This fibrous sheet functions as a continuous envelope, partitioning the musculature into discrete compartments while simultaneously integrating with the surrounding skeletal and vascular architecture.  

This fibrous connective tissue permeates and encircles muscles, bones, nerves, and vasculature, serving as a conduit for mechanical coupling and signaling. Its network includes [aponeuroses](/Aponeuroses), [ligaments](/Ligaments), [tendons](/Tendons), [retinacula](/Retinaculum), [joint capsules](/Joint_capsule), and [septa](/Septum), which collectively transmit forces across the locomotor system. Moreover, the deep fascia envelops every bone surface, covering bone with [periosteum](/Periosteum) and [endosteum](/Endosteum), investing cartilage with [perichondrium](/Perichondrium), and sheathing blood vessels with [tunica externa](/Tunica_externa). Within muscular tissue, the fascia differentiates into [epimysium](/Epimysium), [perimysium](/Perimysium), and [endomysium](/Endomysium), while associated nerves are sheathed by [epineurium](/Epineurium), [perineurium](/Perineurium), and [endoneurium](/Endoneurium). The preponderance of [collagen](/Collagen) fibers confers exceptional tensile strength, whereas the proportion of [elastin](/Elastin) fibers dictates the tissue's capacity for stretch and recoil. &#91;1&#93;

## Examples

Examples include:

• [Fascia lata](/Fascia_lata) – the broad, sheet‑like envelope that invests the thigh, providing a framework for the quadriceps and facilitating lateral transmission of forces.  
• [Deep fascia of leg](/Deep_fascia_of_leg) – a compartmentalized layer that wraps the calf musculature, contributing to ankle stability.  
• [Brachial fascia](/Brachial_fascia) – a dense covering of the upper arm that transmits forces between the shoulder girdle and the forearm.  
• [Buck's fascia](/Buck%27s_fascia) – the deep fascial layer of the abdominal wall that binds the viscera and supports trunk movement.  

## Fascial dynamics

Deep fascia is less extensible than [superficial fascia](/Superficial_fascia). It is essentially [avascular](/Avascular), &#91;2&#93; but is richly [innervated](/Innervated) with [sensory receptors](/Sensory_receptor) that report the presence of pain ([nociceptors](/Nociceptors)); change in movement ([proprioceptors](/Proprioceptors)); change in pressure and vibration ([mechanoreceptors](/Mechanoreceptors)); change in the chemical milieu ([chemoreceptors](/Chemoreceptors)); and fluctuation in temperature ([thermoreceptors](/Thermoreceptors)). &#91;3&#93; &#91;4&#93; These receptors enable the fascia to modulate its tone dynamically—contracting, relaxing, or undergoing compositional remodeling—through processes collectively termed fascial remodeling, &#91;5&#93;.  

Fascia may be able to contract due to the activity of [myofibroblasts](/Myofibroblasts) which may play a role in wound healing. &#91;6&#93;  

The deep fascia can also relax. By monitoring changes in muscular tension, joint position, rate of movement, pressure, and vibration, mechanoreceptors in the deep fascia are capable of initiating relaxation. Deep fascia can relax rapidly in response to sudden muscular overload or rapid movements. [Golgi tendon organs](/Golgi_tendon_organs) operate as a feedback mechanism by causing myofascial relaxation before muscle force becomes so great that tendons might be torn. [Pacinian corpuscles](/Pacinian_corpuscles) sense changes in pressure and vibration to monitor the rate of [acceleration](/Acceleration) of movement. They will initiate a sudden relaxatory response if movement happens too fast. &#91;7&#93; Deep fascia can also relax slowly as some mechanoreceptors respond to changes over longer timescales. Unlike the Golgi tendon organs, Golgi receptors report joint position independent of muscle contraction. This helps the body to know where the bones are at any given moment. [Ruffini endings](/Ruffini_endings) respond to regular stretching and to slow sustained pressure. In addition to initiating fascial relaxation, they contribute to full-body relaxation by inhibiting sympathetic activity which slows down heart rate and respiration. &#91;3&#93; &#91;8&#93;  

When contraction persists, fascia will respond with the addition of new material. Fibroblasts secrete collagen and other proteins into the [extracellular matrix](/Extracellular_matrix) where they bind to existing proteins, making the composition thicker and less extensible. Although this potentiates the [tensile strength](/Tensile_strength) of the fascia, it can unfortunately restrict the very structures it aims to protect. The pathologies resulting from fascial restrictions range from a mild decrease in joint [range of motion](/Range_of_motion) to severe fascial binding of muscles, nerves and blood vessels, as in [compartment syndrome](/Compartment_syndrome) of the leg. However, if fascial contraction can be interrupted long enough, a reverse form of fascial remodeling occurs. The fascia will normalize its composition and tone and the extra material that was generated by prolonged contraction will be ingested by macrophages within the extracellular matrix. &#91;9&#93;  

Like mechanoreceptors, chemoreceptors in deep fascia also have the ability to promote fascial relaxation. We tend to think of relaxation as a good thing, however fascia needs to maintain some degree of tension. This is especially true of ligaments. To maintain joint integrity, they need to provide adequate tension between bony surfaces. If a ligament is too lax, injury becomes more likely. Certain chemicals, including [hormones](/Hormones), can influence the composition of the ligaments. An example of this is seen in the [menstrual cycle](/Menstrual_cycle), where hormones are secreted to create changes in the [uterine](/Uterus) and [pelvic floor](/Pelvic_floor) fascia. The hormones are not site‑specific, however, and chemoreceptors in other ligaments of the body can be receptive to them as well. The ligaments of the knee may be one of the areas where this happens, as a significant association between the [ovulatory](/Ovulation) phase of the menstrual cycle and an increased likelihood for an [anterior cruciate ligament](/Anterior_cruciate_ligament) injury has been demonstrated. &#91;10&#93; &#91;11&#93;  

## Art

The continuity of the deep fasciae within the human body inspired the artistic expression seen in the [Fascial Net Plastination Project](/Fascial_Net_Plastination_Project), which is prominently displayed at the [Body Worlds](/Body_Worlds) exhibition in Berlin. &#91;12&#93;